1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,080
So let's face it, few things in the world manage to ignite national passions like

2
00:00:05,080 --> 00:00:10,240
sports, and in particular football; it's a feeling we all know, right? From the

3
00:00:10,240 --> 00:00:15,679
most die-hard fan to politicians. But, if this collective passion, this fever

4
00:00:15,679 --> 00:00:21,879
that grips us all, could do much more than just fill stadiums, and if it could literally

5
00:00:21,879 --> 00:00:23,559
build a nation?

6
00:00:23,559 --> 00:00:30,439
Yes, I know, the question might seem absurd, almost crazy: can a football match,

7
00:00:30,439 --> 00:00:36,439
no matter how important it is, really have a real, concrete impact on violence, on the ethnic

8
00:00:36,439 --> 00:00:42,239
divisions that, unfortunately, split so many countries? Well, hold on tight, because a

9
00:00:42,239 --> 00:00:47,780
revolutionary study investigated just this in sub-Saharan Africa, and the results, well, are

10
00:00:47,780 --> 00:00:53,539
nothing short of astounding. And let's start right away with the first data point that, honestly, leaves one

11
00:00:53,539 --> 00:00:58,719
speechless. Researchers discovered something incredible. People interviewed right

12
00:00:58,719 --> 00:01:05,140
after a major victory for their national team were 37% less likely

13
00:01:05,140 --> 00:01:11,780
to say "I belong to this ethnic group" instead of saying "I belong to this nation."

14
00:01:11,780 --> 00:01:16,939
Think about it for a moment, it's a huge, profound shift in a person's identity.

15
00:01:16,939 --> 00:01:22,340
And watch out, because this isn't just a feeling, it doesn't just stay in people's

16
00:01:22,340 --> 00:01:27,900
heads. No, no, it turns into something real and tangible. Look here. The countries

17
00:01:27,900 --> 00:01:32,859
that managed to qualify by a whisker for the Africa Cup of Nations saw in the following months

18
00:01:32,859 --> 00:01:37,819
9% fewer civil conflicts. Compared to whom? Compared to those countries that were

19
00:01:37,820 --> 00:01:43,500
narrowly eliminated; less violence, literally, thanks to football. The question at this point

20
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:50,460
is just one: how on earth is this possible? Okay, let's go in order and start from the beginning,

21
00:01:50,460 --> 00:01:55,420
changing minds and hearts. How can you even think of measuring a change

22
00:01:55,420 --> 00:02:00,860
so deep, so intimate, as a person's identity? It seems almost impossible,

23
00:02:00,860 --> 00:02:05,280
right? And yet the key to everything lies in a methodology that is as simple as it is,

24
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:11,560
in my opinion, brilliant. Now, the data source is fundamental for the credibility of all

25
00:02:11,560 --> 00:02:16,560
this. We are talking about the Afrobarometer. It's not just any survey; it's a

26
00:02:16,560 --> 00:02:21,740
massive, highly respected research project that for years has been listening to the opinions of citizens across

27
00:02:21,740 --> 00:02:27,319
Africa on thousands of topics. And among the many questions, there was a very specific one

28
00:02:27,319 --> 00:02:32,080
that is the heart of this first part of the analysis: Do you feel more attached to your nation

29
00:02:32,080 --> 00:02:37,680
or to your ethnic group? And this is where the stroke of genius comes in. Researchers took advantage of

30
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:42,360
something seemingly trivial: randomness. The randomness of when the

31
00:02:42,360 --> 00:02:47,080
interviews were conducted. In practice, they took responses from people from the same country,

32
00:02:47,080 --> 00:02:52,439
of the same ethnicity, interviewed, say, on Tuesday, before the crucial match. And they

33
00:02:52,439 --> 00:02:57,140
compared them with the responses of practically identical people, but interviewed on Thursday after the

34
00:02:57,140 --> 00:03:03,180
match. You see, the only true, major difference between these two groups of people was just

35
00:03:03,180 --> 00:03:09,660
one thing: having experienced the euphoria of victory together. Well, now that we've seen the effect

36
00:03:09,660 --> 00:03:15,220
on the individual, let's look up, moving from the stadium and the individual to

37
00:03:15,220 --> 00:03:20,820
peace and the national level. The question becomes even bigger: how do you prove that a

38
00:03:20,819 --> 00:03:26,180
sporting qualification can seriously reduce violence? Here too, the solution

39
00:03:26,180 --> 00:03:31,419
was ingenious; they used what is called a "natural experiment" in technical jargon. The idea,

40
00:03:31,419 --> 00:03:37,419
in essence, is this: comparing very, very similar countries that played for

41
00:03:37,419 --> 00:03:43,099
everything, qualification until the very last breath. On one side, we have the teams that

42
00:03:43,099 --> 00:03:48,299
made it by a whisker, triggering a crazy wave of euphoria and national unity. On the other side,

43
00:03:48,300 --> 00:03:53,740
those teams excluded by nothing, a detail, a goal difference, a cursed last-minute

44
00:03:53,740 --> 00:03:59,580
goal. You see the point: victory and defeat, in these cases, are almost random, and this allows

45
00:03:59,580 --> 00:04:04,820
for a clean, almost perfect comparison between the effect of joy and that of disappointment.

46
00:04:04,820 --> 00:04:10,740
But let's look at a concrete example to understand exactly what we're talking about. Let's go back in time,

47
00:04:10,740 --> 00:04:17,019
qualifiers for the 2012 Africa Cup of Nations. We're in Group A, it's the final day, and the

48
00:04:17,019 --> 00:04:25,019
tension is sky-high. Look at the standings. Mali with nine points, Zimbabwe with 8, Cape Verde with 7, only

49
00:04:25,019 --> 00:04:31,459
one of them will move forward, one single spot for three nations. And so here's what happens on the pitch: Cape Verde

50
00:04:31,459 --> 00:04:37,620
does its part and beats Zimbabwe 2-1. Meanwhile, in a twist, Mali, who were the favorites,

51
00:04:37,620 --> 00:04:43,779
are only drawing 2-2 against Liberia, who were already eliminated. Can you imagine the tension,

52
00:04:43,780 --> 00:04:49,740
the radios on, the calculations done in real-time. And so we arrive at the final standings. Look,

53
00:04:49,740 --> 00:04:56,180
Mali and Cape Verde both finish with 10 points, tied on points, but who goes through? Mali goes through on

54
00:04:56,180 --> 00:05:01,820
goal difference. A single, measly goal separated the ecstasy of an entire nation from the disappointment

55
00:05:01,820 --> 00:05:07,900
of two others. And here is the key point: it is precisely this thin, almost random margin that

56
00:05:07,900 --> 00:05:12,660
allowed researchers to say, okay, the effect we're measuring is precisely that of victory

57
00:05:12,660 --> 00:05:18,900
and nothing else. Okay, so far we've seen that the effect is real, it can be measured, but

58
00:05:18,900 --> 00:05:24,860
now comes perhaps the most interesting question of all. Why? Why does it work, what are

59
00:05:24,860 --> 00:05:29,100
the mechanisms, the psychological and social triggers, that a simple football match manages

60
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:35,540
to trigger with such overwhelming force? Well, research tells us something important.

61
00:05:35,540 --> 00:05:41,620
Beware, not all victories are equal. The effect, for instance, is almost zero for friendlies,

62
00:05:41,620 --> 00:05:47,300
but it explodes, becoming very powerful, for the matches that count, the "do or die" ones. And the effect

63
00:05:47,300 --> 00:05:52,780
is even stronger if you beat a long-time, historical rival, but that's not all. There's another

64
00:05:52,780 --> 00:05:58,020
crazy data point. The impact is greater when the national team is a mix of different ethnicities because it becomes

65
00:05:58,020 --> 00:06:03,100
a living example, a model of how people can work together. And finally, the most

66
00:06:03,100 --> 00:06:08,620
powerful victories are the unexpected ones, the David vs. Goliath wins, and those that happen

67
00:06:08,620 --> 00:06:14,100
in countries where the state might be a bit weaker, a bit less present. And all this brings us

68
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:19,500
to the heart of the matter, to the bigger meaning. Here we're not just talking about football, obviously,

69
00:06:19,500 --> 00:06:25,260
we're talking about how a national identity is built, and the fundamental idea, the key concept,

70
00:06:25,260 --> 00:06:31,460
is that of the "imagined community", a term coined by a great historian, Benedict Anderson. There is a

71
00:06:31,460 --> 00:06:36,820
phrase quoted in the study by another historian, Eric Hobsbawm, which I think explains it

72
00:06:36,820 --> 00:06:43,220
perfectly. It goes like this: the imagined community of millions of people seems more real as a

73
00:06:43,220 --> 00:06:50,260
team of 11 named people. Think about it: the nation is a huge, abstract idea, almost impossible

74
00:06:50,260 --> 00:06:55,940
to grasp, but a team—11 people with a name, a face, a story—that is indeed

75
00:06:55,939 --> 00:07:02,100
real. It makes it concrete; in that moment of cheering, every single person feels like part of something

76
00:07:02,100 --> 00:07:07,779
larger, becoming almost a small piece of that nation. So we come to the crucial point.

77
00:07:07,779 --> 00:07:13,939
If an experience so intensely emotional and collective as a football match can, even

78
00:07:13,939 --> 00:07:19,699
temporarily, overcome deep divisions and reduce violence, well, this opens

79
00:07:19,699 --> 00:07:24,180
an incredible window of opportunity. And it leaves us with a question that goes far beyond sport,

80
00:07:24,180 --> 00:07:29,540
a fundamental question: what other shared experiences can we create, what other moments can

81
00:07:29,540 --> 00:07:34,900
have this unifying power, and above all, how can we use them to build communities that

82
00:07:34,900 --> 00:07:37,019
are truly more united and more peaceful.